### Lean 4 Proof with `have` Statements

```lean
theorem global_theorem_le_reasoning (p : Pose)
    (poly : GoodPoly)
    (h_rupert : RupertPose p (convexHull ℝ poly.vertices)) (w : ℝ²) :
    maxInner p poly w ≤ maxOuter p poly w := by
  have h_poly_nonempty : poly.vertices.Nonempty := by sorry
  have h_main : ∀ (y : ℝ), y ∈ (poly.vertices.image fun P => ⟪w, p.inner P⟫) → y ≤ (poly.vertices.image (fun P => ⟪w, p.outer P⟫)).max' (by simp only [Finset.image_nonempty]; exact poly.nonempty) := by sorry
  have h_final : (poly.vertices.image fun P => ⟪w, p.inner P⟫).max' (by simp only [Finset.image_nonempty]; exact poly.nonempty) ≤ (poly.vertices.image (fun P => ⟪w, p.outer P⟫)).max' (by simp only [Finset.image_nonempty]; exact poly.nonempty) := by sorry
  sorry
```

This proof sketch uses `have` statements to break down the problem into smaller, more manageable parts. The first `have` establishes that the set of vertices is nonempty. The second `have` shows that every element in the image of the inner products is bounded above by the maximum of the outer products. The final `have` uses this to compare the maxima of the two sets. 

### Complete Lean 4 Proof

```lean
theorem global_theorem_le_reasoning (p : Pose)
    (poly : GoodPoly)
    (h_rupert : RupertPose p (convexHull ℝ poly.vertices)) (w : ℝ²) :
    maxInner p poly w ≤ maxOuter p poly w := by
  have h_poly_nonempty : poly.vertices.Nonempty := by
    exact Finset.nonempty_iff_ne_empty.mpr (by
      intro h
      have h₁ : poly.vertices = ∅ := h
      rw [h₁] at poly.nonempty
      exact Finset.not_nonempty_empty poly.nonempty)
  
  have h_main : ∀ (y : ℝ), y ∈ (poly.vertices.image fun P => ⟪w, p.inner P⟫) → y ≤ (poly.vertices.image (fun P => ⟪w, p.outer P⟫)).max' (by simp only [Finset.image_nonempty]; exact poly.nonempty) := by
    intro y hy
